                <p>At a small dinner given by the United States Delegation on December 5, general
                    impressions of the work of the Assembly were exchanged and comments were
                    elicited in a wide variety of subjects considered at this [Fourth] session.</p>
                <p>[Here follows a résumé of “the more important items.” Regarding discussion of the
                    work of the Fourth Committee and the “colonial problem”, see <ref target="#pg_368">page 368</ref>.]</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">10. <hi rend="italic">Practice of Consultation</hi>
                </p>
                <p>All those present expressed their appreciation for the consultation practice
                    which the Americans had adopted before the beginning of the Assembly and during
                    the Assembly, especially in connection with the Soviet item. It was unanimously
                    agreed that these practices should be continued both in New York and in the
                    field. In the course of this discussion, Pescatore paid special tribute to the
                    personal relationships <pb facs="0044" n="28" xml:id="pg_28"/> established by
                    Mr. Raynor and the very great value of the work he had done in this sphere.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>D[<hi rend="smallcaps">avid</hi>] H. <hi rend="smallcaps">Popper</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
